Mrs. Merchant is seen at the request of Dr. Emig for evaluation of a sigmoid colon cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Merchant is a 54-year-old female from Bonner, who was undergoing her first colonoscopy screening for a three-month history of rectal bleeding and on April 13, 2010, was found to have a sigmoid colon cancer located approximately 20 cm from the anal verge.  Pathology has been reviewed here and confirmed invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.  She has no family history of colorectal cancer.  She moves her bowels once or twice-a-day.  She has had intermittent problems with constipation in the past which has been stable for her.  She had noticed a little bit of rectal bleeding for the last three-months with wiping and was not overly concerned, and since her insurance did not cover her colonoscopy screening until now, she just recently decided to have a colonoscopy.  The tumor was described as a "semi-circumferential, scalloped mass lesion with a necrotic base."  The exact size was not mentioned.  This was tattooed both proximally and distally.  The prep was good.  She had some diverticula.  She denies recent fatigue.  She has not had significant weight-loss and denies abdominal or rectal pain.  She occasionally has perianal itching.  At times she feels irritation from hemorrhoidal prolapse but never has to manually reduce her hemorrhoids.  She denies fecal incontinence and has no history of anorectal procedures.
In regard to staging, she had a CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis on April 15, 2010, and we have reviewed those images.  This reveals a thickened distal sigmoid colon consistent with her malignancy.  There were some early pericolonic nodes noted.  She had some small, 2- to 3-mm low-attenuation lesions within the right lobe of the liver which were too small to characterize by CT and are indeterminate.  I discussed with Dr. Moore, the radiologist, and he says likely we can only follow these as they are too small for ultrasound and PET scan to determine exactly what they are.

